'''Darryl Jones''' (born December 11, 1961),<ref name="darryljones/bio">{{cite web|url=http://www.darryljones.com/home/frameset_one.htm|title=Darryl Jones BIO|last=Jones|first=Darryl|year=2010|accessdate=31 October 2010}}</ref> also known as "The Munch",<ref name="1995 BassPlayer">{{cite web|url=http://www.abasses.com/darryljones/bassplayer.htm|title=Darryl Jones: Like A Rolling Stone|last=Jisi|first=Chris|date=Jan/Feb 1995|work=Bass Player Magazine: biography and interview|publisher=Bass Player magazine|accessdate=31 October 2010}}</ref> is an [[United States|American]] [[bass guitar]]ist. Jones began his notable career as a [[session musician]], where he gained the experience and confidence to play with some of the most highly regarded recording artists, in [[jazz]], [[Blues music|blues]], and [[rock music]]. Most recently, he has been best known in his role as bassist for [[The Rolling Stones]] since [[Bill Wyman]]'s departure in 1993.

==Career==
[[File:The Rolling Stones with Chuck Leavell and Darryl Jones 2013.jpg|thumb|240px|Jones (right) performing with the Rolling Stones in Boston MA, on June 12, 2013]]
[[File:Darryl Jones in Paris 1983.jpg|thumb|180px|left|Jones performing with the Miles Davis band, Palais des Congr<U+00E8>s, Paris, 1983]]
Jones was born in [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]], [[Illinois]].<ref name="darryljones/bio"/> As a youth, his father, a drummer, supported his musical interests and initially taught his son to play the [[guitar]]. A neighbor who was a [[Bass guitar|bassist]] convinced Darryl to switch to playing the bass instead.<ref name="darryljones/bio"/> Jones attended [[Southern Illinois University Carbondale]]. One musician that Jones first played with in his studio sessions was the nephew of noted jazz musician [[Miles Davis]], Vince Wilburn Jr. He told Jones that Davis was looking for a new bass player, and vouched for him. Jones called Davis, who gave him his first touring gig,<ref name="Bassplayer1">{{cite web|url=http://www.bassplayer.com/article/darryl-jones-stone/jul-05/11380|title=Darryl Jones Stone Unturned|last=Goldsher|first=Alan|year=2009|publisher=''Bass Player'' magazine, New Bay Media|accessdate=7 November 2010}}</ref> and for some years he was mentored by Davis, having joined his band in 1983. As a young prot<U+00E9>g<U+00E9>, Jones played bass guitar on the Miles Davis albums ''[[Decoy (album)|Decoy]]'' (1984) and ''[[You're Under Arrest (Miles Davis album)|You're Under Arrest]]'' (1985). Jones has worked with jazz recording artists who include [[Herbie Hancock|Herbie Hancock's]] [[The Headhunters|Headhunters]], [[Mike Stern]], [[John Scofield]], and [[Steps Ahead]], as well as touring pop and rock artists [[Cher]], [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], [[Peter Gabriel]], [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Eric Clapton]] and [[Joan Armatrading]].

Jones has performed and recorded with [[The Rolling Stones]] since founding bassist [[Bill Wyman]]'s retirement in 1993. In the manner of other tour and recording [[sideman|sidemen]] for the band, such as saxophonist [[Bobby Keys]] and keyboardist [[Chuck Leavell]], Jones' stage movement and audience interaction is low-key and he generally wears understated apparel on stage.{{Citation needed|date=August 2013}} He is a salaried employee and does not share financial participation in the band's worldwide publishing, recording and concert touring revenues.{{Citation needed|date=August 2013}} He is also a member of the [[Stone Raiders]] musical band.

